# gen109 (L17, prose): one-sentence word problems — prose -> arithmetic relation
# -> solve. gen107 solved a symbolic equation; this maps a natural-language
# problem onto an operation chosen from SEMANTIC cues (verbs of gaining/losing/
# grouping/sharing, and comparison phrasings), then computes it. Held-out numbers
# AND held-out verbs, so it is cue-based, not a sentence-template phrasebook. It
# fires only on a "how many/much" question with >= 2 numbers and a known cue, and
# declines otherwise (anti-impostor: never guess an operation).

# Addition: "gets ... more".
> Tom has 6 apples and gets 5 more. How many apples does he have?
< 11.
# The proof shows the relation it read the prose as.
> how do you know?
< Because I read it as 6 + 5 = 11.

# Subtraction: "ate ... left".
> Mary baked 12 cookies and ate 4. How many are left?
< 8.

# Multiplication: "with N ... each".
> There are 7 boxes with 3 balls each. How many balls in total?
< 21.

# Division: "shared among".
> 15 candies are shared among 5 kids. How many does each get?
< 3.

# Held-out VERB ("loses" was never in an earlier case) still maps to subtraction.
> Sam has 9 marbles and loses 2. How many does he have?
< 7.

# Comparison is the subtle one: bare "more" means addition, but "how many MORE
# ... than" is a difference -> subtraction. The cue priority gets it right.
> Anna has 10 stamps and Ben has 4. How many more does Anna have?
< 6.

# No two numbers / no operation cue -> decline honestly, never fabricate.
> The sky is blue. How many clouds are there?
< I don't understand that yet.